&nbsp;AGI -&nbsp;After months of negotiations, pressures and shortened demands, the effort of the Biden administration has been successful: the House of Representatives of the United States has given way to so much anticipated new aid in favor of Ukraine, Israel and Taiwan for a total of 95 billion dollars. The bills were passed in rapid succession with a overwhelming bipartisan vote, although they leave some doubts about the future of the speaker Mike Johnson, in the sight of ultra conservative exponents.
&nbsp;
American President Joe Biden welcomed the decision, stressing that the approved packages "will provide fundamental support to Israel and Ukraine; will provide desperately necessary humanitarian aid to Gaza, Sudan, Haiti and other locations... and will strengthen security and stability in the Indo-Pacific." The White House leader praised the members who joined by overcoming the party lines "to respond to the call of History".
&nbsp;
Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyj also celebrated the House's free path to aid, claiming that "they will urge the war to expand, save thousands and thousands of lives and help both our nations become stronger." "We hope that bills will be supported by the Senate and sent to President Biden's signature. Thank you, America!", concluded Kiev leader on X. In this regard, the Senate could approve the bill already next Tuesday, let the democratic leader of the House Chuck Schumer know.
&nbsp;
Moscow's reaction lasts, according to which the new aid "will aggravate the global crisis", as accused the spokesman of the Foreign Ministry Maria Zakharova. The approved package "will further enrich the United States and ruin Ukraine even more, killing even more Ukrainians due to the Kiev regime," said the Kremlin spokesman, Dmitri Peskov.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
&nbsp; The approval of the new aids to Ukraine - almost 61 billion dollars - comes after for almost a year and a half the Congress did not approve large-scale financing in favor of Kiev, mainly because of the crossed vetoes. It is the fulfillment of months of work of Biden and Democrats at Congress to overcome the opposition of a part of the Republicans, near Donald Trump, and come to help the Ukrainian ally in difficulty against Russian troops. The financing of the war has become a dispute in view of the November presidential elections that will probably once again see Biden against Trump.
&nbsp;
The Speaker of the Chamber, Republican Johnson, after months of hesitation, finally expressed his support for the package for Ukraine and the fist of ultra-conservative Republicans, who had threatened his hunt if he insisted on this line, seemed to retreat, at least temporarily. The bill on Ukraine will also allow Biden to confiscate and sell Russian goods and provide money to Kiev to finance reconstruction, a move that found the support of other G7 nations.
&nbsp;
US MEPs also approved a total of $26 billion in emergency assistance to Israel, including nearly $14 billion in military aid for its war against Hamas in Gaza. The funds will be used primarily to strengthen the Iron Dome air defense system. In the overall figure there are also $9 billion allocated to address "the desperate need for humanitarian assistance for Gaza and other vulnerable populations worldwide".
&nbsp;
To all this, there are several billion dollars destined to arm Taiwan and the measure that previews the ban of TikTok in the U.S. in case it did not cut its ties with China. A perspective that aroused the harsh reaction of the platform, controlled by the Chinese group ByteDance: such a maneuver would mean "violent freedom of expression" of 170 million Americans, a spokesman commented. Not to mention, he added, that the proposed ban "would be 7 million companies and would close a platform that contributes to the US economy for $24 billion a year". &nbsp;
