&nbsp;
"We have come to the point where the balance between the use of resources and the well-being of the population has broken, especially in the last year," said Víctor Martín, spokesman for the Canarian collective if Agota (the Canary Islands have enough), who is helping to coordinate Saturday protests in the eight islands.
Eleven members of "Canarias seagota" are already on hunger strike > from a week to protest against the construction of two large luxury complexes in southern Tenerife, which define "illegal" and totally useless.
&nbsp;
Last year, 13.9 million people visited the islands, which have a population of 2.2 million. Although tourism accounts for about 35% of the archipelago's GDP - with a revenue of EUR 16.9 billion only in 2022 - the local population claims that industry is stressing natural resources and is extruding them from the rental market.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
The data of the National Institute of Spanish Statistics show that 33.8% of people in the Canary Islands are at risk of poverty or social exclusion, the highest percentage for any region except Andalusia.
&nbsp;
Martín said that the continuous attention of the regional government to tourism at a time when the climate emergency was leading to cuts in water supplies made no sense. “The question [of water] is increasing in urban areas where there are more tourists,” he said. “We had a very dry winter and in Tenerife it has already been declared the water emergency and “There will be restrictions if it will not rain more this month, but here at this time there are 36°C. All this is unsustainable and means that we will not even be able to maintain normal levels of tourism. Yet the authorities and enterprises here are trying to stick to this model.”
&nbsp;
“The problem is not tourists,” he said. “It is a model built around – and with the connivence of – an entrepreneurial class that does not want to listen to what needs to be done, and with a political class that serves that business class instead of serving all citizens.”
He said that a complete rethink of the Canary Islands tourist model cannot wait. "What we ask is very simple: Since tourism is the main economic activity and the cause of all these problems, we want the immediate stop to these two megaprojects," he said referring to developments in Tenerife.
&nbsp;
Fernando Clavijo, regional president of the Canary Islands, said that his government is already acting. “All the actions undertaken by this government are based on a review of this model,” he told journalists this week. “The Canary Islands tourist model has been successful, but of course, as in everything, there are things that could be perfected.”
